def plot_histograms(data, title_1, title_2, color):
    """
    Create histograms
    =================
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    data : pandas dataframe or series
           Data for prediction
    
    title_1 : string
              Title of the first histogram.

    title_2 : string
              Title of the first histogram.
    
    color : string
            Color for histogram.
            
    Returns:
    --------
    None
    
    Output:
    -------
    2 normal histograms. Difference between histograms is the number of bins.
    """
    len_data = len(data)
    
    min_value = int(data.min())
    max_value = int(ceil(data.max()))
    
    bins_1 = max_value - min_value
    if len_data >= 1000:
        bins_2 = 1000
    else:
        bins_2 = len_data
    
    f = plt.figure()
    f.set_figwidth(20)
    
    h1 = f.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)
    h1.set_title('{}'.format(title_1))
    
    for element in ([h1.title, h1.xaxis.label, h1.yaxis.label] + h1.get_xticklabels() + h1.get_yticklabels()):
        element.set_fontsize(20)
    
    h1.axes.set_xlim(xmin= min_value, xmax=max_value)
    plt.hist(data, bins=bins_1, color=color)

    h2 = f.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)
    h2.set_title('{}'.format(title_2))

    for element in ([h2.title, h2.xaxis.label, h2.yaxis.label] + h2.get_xticklabels() + h2.get_yticklabels()):
        element.set_fontsize(20)
    
    h2.axes.set_xlim(xmin= min_value, xmax=max_value)
    plt.hist(data, bins=bins_2, color=color)
    
    plt.show()

    
    
def plot_histograms_cumulative(data, title_1, title_2, color):  
    """
    Create cumulative histograms
    ============================
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    data : pandas dataframe or series
           Data for prediction
    
    title_1 : string
              Title of the first histogram.

    title_2 : string
              Title of the first histogram.
    
    color : string
            Color for histogram.
            
    Returns:
    --------
    None
    
    Output:
    -------
    2 cumulative histograms. Difference between histograms is the number of bins.
    """    
    
    len_data = len(data)
    
    min_value = int(data.min())
    max_value = int(ceil(data.max()))
    
    bins_1 = max_value - min_value
    if len_data >= 1000:
        bins_2 = 1000
    else:
        bins_2 = len_data
    
    f = plt.figure()
    f.set_figwidth(20)
    
    h1 = f.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)
    h1.set_title('{}'.format(title_1))
    
    for element in ([h1.title, h1.xaxis.label, h1.yaxis.label]
                    + h1.get_xticklabels()
                    + h1.get_yticklabels()):
        element.set_fontsize(20)
    
    h1.axes.set_xlim(xmin= min_value, xmax=max_value)
    plt.hist(data, bins=bins_1, color=color, cumulative=True)

    h2 = f.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)
    h2.set_title('{}'.format(title_2))

    for element in ([h2.title, h2.xaxis.label, h2.yaxis.label]
                    + h2.get_xticklabels()
                    + h2.get_yticklabels()):
        element.set_fontsize(20)
    
    h2.axes.set_xlim(xmin= min_value, xmax=max_value)
    plt.hist(data, bins=bins_2, color=color, cumulative=True)
    
    plt.show()

All three dataset has the same format with the following columns (header : type):

  • Time : object (actually string)
  • windSpeed (m/s) : float64
  • windDic (degree) : float64

Pandas sense values of Time column is object (string) since the format of time does not meet the requirements of timestamp or time value. The leading zero is missing before the hours. In Python it has to converted before training a model.

It is important to highlight that output of describe() can be deceptive under the windDic (degree) column. Since it contains degree values, there are special meanings of min and max values. It represents that the wind does not blow from every angle. Maybe this nearly 3 degree does not seem to huge, but in the real life a new building or a landscaping can be harmful to wind farms.

Cleaning both measurement datasets from invalid entries¶

There are entries that contains data that slow the learning process and decrease the convergence.

  • Since AvailableMW means the maximum capacity at the moment, every records are meaningless where AvailableMW = 0

# removing record where ratio > 1.0 and windspeed is slower than 12 m/s

print('Dataset 1:')
actual_remove = len(dataset1_measurement_clean[(dataset1_measurement_clean['ratio'] > 1.0) & (dataset1_measurement_clean['windSpeed'] < 12)])
removed_records_1 += actual_remove
print('{} record(s) removed.'.format(actual_remove))
indexnames = dataset1_measurement_clean[(dataset1_measurement_clean['ratio'] > 1.0) & (dataset1_measurement_clean['windSpeed'] < 12)].index
dataset1_measurement_clean.drop(indexnames, inplace = True)
print('New length of dataset is {} record(s).'.format(len(dataset1_measurement_clean)))

print('\nDataset 2:')
actual_remove = len(dataset2_measurement_clean[(dataset2_measurement_clean['ratio'] > 1.0) & (dataset2_measurement_clean['windSpeed'] < 12)])
removed_records_2 += actual_remove
print('{} record(s) removed.'.format(actual_remove))
indexnames = dataset2_measurement_clean[(dataset2_measurement_clean['ratio'] > 1.0) & (dataset2_measurement_clean['windSpeed'] < 12)].index
dataset2_measurement_clean.drop(indexnames, inplace = True)

Summary¶

Forecast datasets contains the records in a right way compared with the measurement datasets. The last ones contains invalid non-numeric and incomprehensible records. There are a lof of records where values in availableMW are lower than values in windPower.
